WEBVTT

00:01.058 --> 00:10.168
being in Sweden and talking about joy reminds me of a story I've heard from John Piper over the years.

00:12.010 --> 00:14.694
It gets at the heart of what real joy is.

00:15.414 --> 00:17.216
And I'm just talking joy this weekend.

00:17.236 --> 00:18.498
We're talking real joy.

00:19.980 --> 00:29.170
And a common misunderstanding might be as we talk about real joy that the joy is external.

00:30.370 --> 00:39.602
and it's enthusiastic and it radiates like Trevor or it's loud like an American.

00:42.866 --> 00:44.128
We're talking about real joy.

00:44.348 --> 00:47.612
We're talking about joy in the heart first and foremost.

00:48.053 --> 00:58.386
It will have external manifestations of various sorts in actions and words through different personality types and different

00:58.690 --> 01:03.317
nationality bets, which brings about this story.

01:04.238 --> 01:18.259
You should be really hopeful that John Piper ministered 33 years in Minneapolis, Minnesota with a lot of Swedish ancestors, Swedish descendants in Minneapolis.

01:19.201 --> 01:28.274
And there was a man who came up to him one time and John's talking about joy and he came up and said, I have a Swedish personality.

01:29.154 --> 01:36.223
When my son kicked the winning field goal, this is American football, field goals.

01:36.803 --> 01:40.408
American football, where we don't really use our feet much, is a little kicking.

01:41.609 --> 01:42.070
Not much.

01:42.710 --> 01:45.654
And then when you kick it to either one point or three points, it's very confusing.

01:46.115 --> 01:47.156
Mainly use our hands.

01:48.598 --> 01:54.505
He kicked the winning field goal in the state championship game, and I think this brother's name was Arnie.

01:55.266 --> 01:58.930
He was a happy Swedish descendant, and he

02:05.826 --> 02:09.910
And for Arnie, that was real joy, humanly speaking.

02:09.950 --> 02:10.831
It was natural joy.

02:12.352 --> 02:20.881
So how these things get fleshed out through our personalities, through our faces, our words, our volume, that's going to be different.

02:21.922 --> 02:23.323
That's not the joy we're talking about.

02:23.343 --> 02:27.587
We're talking about the real joy in the soul this morning.

02:29.729 --> 02:34.354
Last night we saw from Isaiah 55 and from elsewhere in the Bible,

02:34.498 --> 02:45.775
that God made us for His glory and God made us for that real joy, that internal joy of the soul in Him.

02:45.835 --> 02:58.513
And we saw that these two pursuits, His glory, our joy, are one amazing pursuit because God is most glorified in us when we are most satisfied in Him.

02:58.533 --> 03:04.402
I think I mentioned last night, I would tell you a little bit more of my story.

03:05.794 --> 03:13.346
At age 19, I was a freshman at Furman University in Greenville, South Carolina.

03:13.366 --> 03:31.916
Age 19, when I first read and then reread, and reread and reread the book Desiring God, John has his own ways of using the English language.

03:31.936 --> 03:33.298
And so it took some rereading.

03:33.986 --> 03:35.608
find out exactly what he's talking about.

03:35.628 --> 03:40.835
So joy and delight and contentment and satisfaction.

03:40.895 --> 03:43.458
These are all various ways, talking about Christian joy.

03:43.698 --> 03:47.884
These are not distinct terms as if joy and delight and happiness are different.

03:48.264 --> 03:50.527
They're different ways of talking about the same reality.

03:52.249 --> 04:02.482
And as I began to understand this message of God's pursuit of glory and my pursuit of joy being one, this is almost too good to be true.

04:03.938 --> 04:17.240
I began to experience real joy in God, I think, for the first time, even having grown up in church, something was new, something changed.

04:19.524 --> 04:30.642
I knew from Scripture and my upbringing and from reason that it was right for God to be glorified, the God who made the world deserves glory for it.

04:31.778 --> 04:43.297
And I knew from my own heart that I wanted joy, not thin and empty and fake joy, but thick and full, real joy.

04:46.361 --> 04:50.688
And so I began to consciously experience that for the first time in learning about that.

04:50.729 --> 04:53.192
And yet, my joy was not perfect.

04:54.334 --> 04:55.837
Still isn't, not yet.

04:58.060 --> 04:59.122
Not sinless.

05:00.642 --> 05:03.586
Not undiluted, not yet.

05:05.289 --> 05:10.657
But after a while, I realized something was missing for me.

05:10.697 --> 05:16.065
There was a peace that was missing to my own fault, not John Piper's.

05:17.147 --> 05:22.875
Actually, I got help from John Piper in his little book called Seeing and Savoring Jesus Christ.

05:24.298 --> 05:29.906
But for me, after a while, I started to think, what about Jesus?

05:30.402 --> 05:38.033
All this talk of God and his glory and this focus on my joy and being satisfied in him, where does Jesus come in?

05:38.073 --> 05:39.134
Where does he fit?

05:40.436 --> 05:43.080
Is there a place for Jesus in this system?

05:43.140 --> 05:47.165
And so that's what we're tackling here this morning.

05:47.225 --> 05:48.487
That's our question this morning.

05:48.808 --> 05:50.910
What about Jesus?

05:52.973 --> 05:56.338
And in answering that question related to the God man,

05:57.474 --> 06:05.382
My quick summary of Jesus as God man is he's fully God, fully man in one spectacular person.

06:06.623 --> 06:17.694
And as we focus this morning on him as the God man, we go deeper, both in God's pursuit of his glory and in our pursuit of joy.

06:18.756 --> 06:25.202
Now we did see last night with that strange mention of David, right David?

06:26.338 --> 06:28.620
David's greater son that's prophesied.

06:28.680 --> 06:34.006
