07:02.173 --> 07:14.424
The water, the milk, the wine, the feast of Isaiah 55 we saw are without cost because Jesus, the suffering servant, made the costly purchase.

07:17.147 --> 07:21.311
So there's some of how Jesus fits.

07:23.413 --> 07:24.274
He bought

07:24.738 --> 07:25.259
the feast.

07:26.040 --> 07:30.586
He makes the invitation possible, but is there more?

07:32.148 --> 07:35.493
Is there more place for Jesus in the system?

07:37.075 --> 07:53.938
So this morning we turn to the New Testament and we turn to the earthly life of Jesus and we ask, what does this vision that we're talking about this weekend of real joy to the glory of God look like in the human life of Christ?

07:54.338 --> 07:57.582
How did God himself in human flesh live it out?

07:59.224 --> 08:02.789
Did Jesus as God pursue his own glory?

08:04.250 --> 08:09.237
And did Jesus as man live like a joy seeker?

08:09.297 --> 08:16.946
And how might that confirm and deepen what we celebrated last night?

08:18.068 --> 08:22.994
Now last night we saw that great summary quote from Jonathan Edwards,

08:23.586 --> 08:26.951
about God's final goal, his highest aim and all he does.

08:27.392 --> 08:37.247
Edward says, all that is ever spoken of in Scripture as an ultimate end of God's works is included in that one phrase, the glory of God.

08:38.909 --> 08:44.017
Some of us like to call this God's God-centeredness.

08:46.080 --> 08:52.530
That God, righteously, justly, wonderfully, lovingly,

08:53.954 --> 08:56.737
is at the center of God's own life.

08:56.857 --> 08:57.258
Enjoy.

08:57.678 --> 08:59.560
This is God's God's centeredness.

09:01.362 --> 09:11.333
Biblically shaped minds sense the rightness of this, that God is the infinitely valuable creator compared to his creatures.

09:12.594 --> 09:18.821
And yet, the incarnation of the Son of God raises new questions.

09:21.064 --> 09:23.186
Like, what happens

09:23.394 --> 09:33.990
when the Creator Himself in the eternal person of the Son takes on our full humanity and in this way becomes a creature with us in the created world.

09:35.012 --> 09:38.076
This is amazing how the author enters the story.

09:40.700 --> 09:48.853
How does the earthly life of Jesus, the God-man from birth to the cross relate to God's God-centeredness?

09:50.735 --> 09:52.498
And how does this God-centeredness

09:52.578 --> 10:04.430
relate to Christ's own glorification, beginning with the cross and the resurrection and including his ascension and his sitting down at on the throne of heaven.

10:07.673 --> 10:20.786
Key to answering questions like those will be our need to see progress across time in the human life of Jesus as he moves through his life.

10:21.154 --> 10:31.586
as Jesus moves from Bethlehem to Galilee to Calvary to heaven in the Ascension.

10:32.808 --> 10:40.036
So instead of simply pressing for a timeless answer to the question, did Jesus seek his own glory?

10:40.056 --> 10:40.897
You can ask that question.

10:41.137 --> 10:42.559
Did Jesus seek his own glory?

10:45.222 --> 10:48.786
I think when he do resist giving a timeless answer,

10:48.994 --> 10:59.088
and we need to track with the sequence of the life of Christ and see how God's great plan unfolds in the life of Jesus.

10:59.628 --> 11:03.694
Jesus' pursuit of glory and joy is complex.

11:04.675 --> 11:05.436
It's layered.

11:06.398 --> 11:12.386
It's dynamic as he moves from the manger to the cross to the resurrection.

11:14.088 --> 11:18.354
So let me state plainly here at the beginning what our interest is.

11:18.562 --> 11:18.983
in this.

11:20.245 --> 11:21.807
